<div class='communityQuestion'>
<div class='questionText'>
<a href="/questions/852326-how-was-john-smith-an-influential-figure">how was john smith an influential figure in this book?</a>
</div>
<div class='communityQAFooter questionFooter'>
<ul class='questionFooterActions'>
<li class='footerItem like'>
<span class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_community_question_852326'><a id="like_count_community_question_852326" rel="nofollow" href="/rating/voters/852326?resource_type=CommunityQuestion"><span class="likesCount">2 likes</span></a>&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;<a rel="nofollow" class="jsLike like_it" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F9862761-1493">like</a></span>

</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionTimestamp'>
<a href="/questions/852326-how-was-john-smith-an-influential-figure">5 years ago</a>
</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionPermalink'>
<a href="/questions/852326-how-was-john-smith-an-influential-figure">Add your answer</a>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

</div>
<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/63084373-diana-cramer"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1482855151i/63084373._UX100_CR0,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/63084373-diana-cramer">Diana Cramer</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">The book is not one of those &quot;A year of...&quot; books... to trace the scope of the Columbian Exchange, it necessarily covers events and figures beyond *ju<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">The book is not one of those "A year of..." books... to trace the scope of the Columbian Exchange, it necessarily covers events and figures beyond *just* 1493.<br />Captain John Smith does figure in this book because of the Colony of Virginia, his role in the establishment of Jamestown (which is controversial), and among other things, because treatment of John Smith and other colonial adventurers needs to be counterbalanced. Particularly the idea of the white colonizer coming to a thinly-populated wilderness to subdue it.<br />Highly recommend that you read the book and find out!<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
